UPON ARRIVAL AT HIS NEXT STOP, THE DRIVER OPENED THE DOORS OF HIS TRAILER AND FOUND SMOKE AND A SMALL FIRE IN THE TRAILER. THE STOWED BAG HAD SELF IGNITED, THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO EXTINGUISH FIRE WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. THE FIRE REPEATEDLY RE-IGNITED. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS SUMMONS AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. THE TANK SUSTAINED NO DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE. THE TRAILER AND TWO OTHER SHIPMENTS SUSTAINED MINOR DAMAGE. AT ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR AUTHORIZATION TO RETURN THE TANK. NO ONE COULD BE REACHED AT THE SHIPPER AS IT WAS AFTER NORMAL BUSINESS AT THAT TIME. SINCE THE TANK WAS NO LONGER LEAKING, IT WAS TRANSPORTED TO RTS'S TERMINAL IN MILWAUKEE, WI. THE TANK DID NOT LEAK WHILE IN TRANSIT TO MILWAUKEE. THERE WAS ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE OVER-NIGHT WHILE THE TANK RESTED ON RTS'S DOCK. SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THE NEXT MORNING AND SENT A CREW TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO A NEW TANK.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION EVENT LOCATED AT 6201 KELLOGG AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH, TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM OF A CUBIC YARD FIBERBOARD BOX ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE COVER OF ONE OF THE INDIVIDUAL PAINT CANS PACKAGED WITHIN THE BOX HAD DISLODGED ALLOWING MATERIAL TO SATURATE THE FIBERBOARD WALL OF THE PACKAGE.  IN ADDITION, SUFFICIENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS NOT USED TO ABSORB THE LIQUID THAT DID ESCAPE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE RE-PACKAGED INTO A NEW CUBIC YARD BOX ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. ******* IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, INDIVIDUALS RESPONSIBLE FOR PACKAGING CONTAINERS IN THE FIELD HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL INNER CONTAINERS ARE PROPERLY SEALED AND SUFFICIENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL IS UTILIZED TO BOTH CUSHION THE INNER PACKAGES AS WELL AS ABSORB ANY LIQUID IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER OPENS DURING TRANSPORTATION.

- CARGO ARRIVED CAROTRANS LOS ANGELES DOCK LATE MORNING OF 10/7/96 FROM CAROTRANS HOUSTON ON HYUNDAI CONTAINER NUMBER HDMU 6071209.  - LOS ANGELES TERMINAL BEGAN TO UNLOAD CONTAINER AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM ON MONDAY 10/7/96.  CARGO WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED PROPERLY WITH 3 - 4 X 6'S ACROSS THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER.  A PIECE OF 1/2 PLY WOOD WAS BEHIND THE 4 X 6'S SEPARATING THE BRACING FROM THE PRODUCT.  - THERE WAS NO VISIBLE DAMAGE EVIDENT UPON REMOVAL OF THE BLOCKING AND BRACING.  - WHEN THE DOCK MAN REMOVED THE FIRST PALLET FROM THE CONTAINER, HE WALKED AROUND THE PALLET TO INSPECT BEFORE MOVING TO THE HAZARDOUS STORAGE AREA.  - ON INSPECTION OF THE PALLET, THE DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED THAT A MIDDLE BOX ON THE SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET APPEARED TO BE WET.  - THE DOCK WORKER IMMEDIATELY CLEARED DOCK OF PERSONNEL AND NOTIFIED A SUPERVISOR.  - SUPERVISOR TOOK NOT OF APPARENT DAMAGE AND ISOLATED THE PALLET TO REMOVE THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  - WHEN PALLET WAS BROKEN DOWN AND LEAKING BOX WAS OPENED FOR EXAMINATION AND INSPECTION, IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WERE NO PUNCTURE MARKS IN THE OUTER BOX OR ON THE INNER PLASTIC CONTAINER, AND THE TOP OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINER IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE LID WAS WET.  FURTHER EXAMINATION REVEALED THAT THE SCREW TOP LID OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINER WAS LOOSE.  WHEN THE TOP WAS OPENED AND PRODUCT WAS EXAMINED IT APPEARED TO STILL BE FULL. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL AND PRODUCT LOSS APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED DUE TO AN UNSECURED LID ON THE PLASTIC CONTAINER.  WE ESTIMATE THAT NO MORE THAN 3 TO 4 OUNCES OF PRODUCT WAS LOST OR SPILLED.  - THE PLASTIC CONTAINER AND CARDBOARD PACKAGING WERE PLACED IN A PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM FOR INSTRUCTION FROM SHIPPER AS TO DISPOSITION.  - SEVERAL BOXES SURROUNDING THE LEAKING PACKAGE RECEIVED RESIDUAL CARTON DAMAGE AND ARE WET AND NEED TO BE REPLACED.  - THE CARGO WAS LOADED AND STOWED IN A PROPER FASHION.  IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT MANUFACTURER INITIATE A PROCEDURE TO INSPECT ALL PACKAGES TO INSURE LIDS ARE AFFIXED IN A SECURE MANNER TO ELIMINATE SIMILAR OCCURRENCES.

column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS REFUSED BY THE RECIPIENT BECAUSE ONE CORNER OF THE BOX WAS WET.  THE PACKAGE WAS RETURNED TO THE STATION WHERE IT WAS OPENED. UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND THE FOUR BOTTLES ON THEIR SIDES.  AS THERE WAS NO ORIENTATION ARROWS ON THE BOX, WHAT WOULD NORMALLY BE PERCEIVED AS THE TOP OF THE BOX (WITH THE FLAPS) WAS NOT THE TRUE OR CORRECT ORIENTATION BASED ON THE INNER CONTAINERS.  IT APPEARS THAT ONE OF THE BOTTLES COMPLETELY WAS EMPTY OF ITS CONTENTS.  THE INT'L AIR WAYBILL INDICATED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE SILVER NITRATE-NON HAZARDOUS.  HOWEVER THE LABEL ON THE INNER BOTTLES INDICATES THAT THE MATERIAL IS IN FACT AN OXIDIZER.  BASED ON THAT INFORMATION, I NOTIFIED THE WESTERN REGION FAA DUTY OFFICER.  THAT PERSON CONNECTED ME WITH MARGE RADCLIFFE, THE FAA LAS CASFO MGR.  I GAVE MARGE A RUNDOWN OF EVENTS AND ADVISED THAT WE WOULD HOLD THE SHIPMENT UNTIL IT CAN BE INSPECTED.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  IN FACT JUST THE OPPOSITE WAS TRUE WITH THE AIRBILL STATEMENT.  THE SHIPPER WILL BE NOTIFIED ON 10/9/96.

column168: A VACUUM TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM UNITED TECHNOLOGIES CORPORATION LOCATED AT 415 WASHINGTON AVENUE IN NORTH HAVEN, CT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXMATELY 1-2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAVEL VALVE OF THE VACUUM TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA OF THE RECEIVING FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. THE CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL. AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK TRUCK DETERMINED THAT THE TRAVEL VALVE DID NOT SEAT PROPERLY WHEN IT WAS CLOSED THEREBY ALLOWING THE SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE VALVE. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO CONDUCT PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS TO IDENTIFY ANY CONDITIONS THAT COULD COMPROMISE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE PACKAGE.

column168: UTLX 803651 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS AFTER LOCAL CITIZEN NOTIFIED FIRE DEPARTMENT OF GAS ODOR IN AREA OF RAIL SIDING. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND FOUND A SLIGHT LEAK WAS ORIGINATING FROM THE SAFETY VALVE ASSEMBLY. AIR MONITORING INDICATED THE LEAK WAS WITHIN ACCEPTABLE LIMITS FOR SAFETY WORKING AROUND THE CAR. 15 LOCAL RESIDENTS WHO HAD BEEN EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOUSES AFTER ABOUT 2 HOURS. REPEATED ATTEMPTS TO CAP AND CONTROL THE LEAK WERE UNSUCCESSFUL. THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS, CARRIER AND SHIPPER OFFICIALS, AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE REPRESENTATIVES AGREED THE SAFEST RESOLUTION OF THIS INCIDENT WOULD BE TO MOVE THE CAR TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION APPROXIMATELY 15 MILES AWAY FOR UNLOADING. THE APPROPRIATE FRA REGIONAL OFFICALS WERE CONTACTED AND CONCURRED ON THE MOVEMENT OF THE CAR. AN EMERGENCY EXEMPTION WAS ISSUED AND THE CAR WAS PLACED FOR UNLOADING BY SPECIAL TRAIN MOVEMENT AT 1:00 PM, OCTOBER 13, 1996.

DRIVER AND CONSIGNEE UNLOADER MADE HOOK UP, OPENED CARGO TANK VALVES AND STORAGE TANK VALVES AND STARTED TO PRESSURIZE CARGO TANK. WHEN PRESSURE REACHED 18 LLS., CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEE WENT TO CHECK THE STORAGE TANK AND THE DRIVER WENT AND SAT DOWN ON THE STAIRS TO THE RIGHT AND REAR OF THE CARGO TANK. WITHIN APPROXIMATELY 1 MINUTE THE HOSE BLEW OFF THE QUICK COUPLER REDUCER FITTING AND PRODUCT SPLASHED ON THE DRIVER, UNDER HIS FACE SHIELD, SAFETY GLASSES AND INTO HIS EYES. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED TO SEE EYE DOCTOR. APPROX. 600 GALLONS RELEASED INTO PLANT SEWER WHICH GOES TO TREATMENT PLANT. ONCE TREATED IT IS THEN SENT TO CITY SEWER. ALL PRODUCT RELEASED INSIDE BUILDING AND CONTAINED TO KAL KAN PLANT.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MEBANE PACKAGING LOCATED AT 248 WARFORD AVENUE IN MEMPHIS, TN TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE SHIPMENT TO A SECOND TRAILER FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION. DURING THE TRANSFER OF DRUMS FROM ONE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER, ONE OF THE 55 GALLON CONTAINERS WAS PUNCTURED WHEN IT STRUCK THE SIDE WALL OF THE VAN TRAILER AS THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR LOWERED THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL TO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DRUM INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. ** IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE FORK-LIFT OPERATOR HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO PAY CLOSE ATTENTION TO ALL LOADING AREAS AND TO AVOID SHARP EDGES AND/OR OBJECTS THAT COULD DAMAGE THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL OF A PACKAGE.

column168: THE PICKUP REQUESTED BY SCIENTIFIC ECOLOGY REQUIRED TWO TANKERS.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 11,000 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC MATERIAL TO BE PUMPED (5,500 PER TANKERS).  OF THE TWO TANKERS SENT, ONE WAS A VACUUM TANKER AND THE OTHER WAS A BULK TANKER.  THE VACUUM TANKER IS USED ITSELF AND THE BULK TANKER.  THE TRANSFER IS ACCOMPLISHED BY (1) REVERSING THE PUMP FROM VACUUM TO PRESSURE, CREATING PRESSURE IN THE TANK WHICH FORCES THE MATERIAL FROM THE VACUUM TANKER INTO THE BULK TANKER.  DURING THE TRANSFER, ED DENNIS CLIMBED UP ON THE BULK TANKER RECEIVING THE LOAD, TO OBSERVE THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL IN THE TANK.  AT THE TIME HE LOOKED INTO THE TANK, THE TRANSFER COMPLETES, ALLOWING SOME AIR TO TRAVEL THROUGH THE HOSE AND MATERIAL CREATING A BUBBLING EFFFECT WHICH PRODUCED THE SPLASHOVER.  THIS IN TURN CAUSED A MINOR SPILL AND ALSO SPLASHED ON THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT WEARING HIS PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT; HOWEVER HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FOR VERY MINOR BURNS.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION EVENT LOCATED AT 356 THREE RIVERS PARKWAY IN ADDYSTON, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM AND SIDE OF A 55 GALLON DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA WHERE THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND DETERMINED THROUGH FIELD ANALYSIS POLYETHYLENE CONTAINER. ALL SPILL DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE DECONTAMINATION OF THE VAN TRAILER AND ASPHALT PARKING AND WAS PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL. ** AN INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT HAS DETERMINED THAT AN ACIDIC HOUSEHOLD CLEANING COMPOUND WAS INADVERTENTLY CONSOLIDATED A DRUM CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. THE ACIDIC MATERIAL DEGRADED THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL OF THE CARBON STEEL DRUM RESULTING IN THE FORMATION OF SEVERAL HOLES IN THE SIDE AND BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER. ** IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT CLEAN HARBORS HAS INCORPORATED A "BUCKET TESTING" PROCEDURE FOR ALL MATERIALS DESIGNATED FOR THE FUEL CONSOLIDATION PROGRAM AT HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION EVENTS. THIS PROCEDURE WILL INVOLVE MIXING A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE MATERIAL BEING CONSOLIDATED INTO A COMPOSITE SAMPLE OF OTHER MATERIAL BEING CONSOLIDATED IN ORDER TO INSURE COMPATIBILITY. FURTHERMORE, CLEAN HARBORS CURRENTLY ASSIGNS A TRAINED CHEMIST TO SUPERVISE THE SEGREGATION OF HOUSEHOLD MATERIALS DELIVERED TO A COLLECTION LOCATION TO INSURE THAT EACH "LAB PACK" IS PACKAGED MATERIALS ARE DESIGNATED TO BE CONSOLIDATED. CLEAN HARBORS WILL NOW REQUIRE A TRAINED CHEMIST TO SUPERVISE THE ACTUAL CONSOLIDATION PROCESS TO INSURE THAT ONLY COMPATIBLE FUELS ARE CONSOLIDATED. THE UPDATED PROCEDURES LISTED ABOVE WILL BE DOCUMENTED AND DISTRIBUTED TO ALL SITE SUPERVISORS PRIOR TO CONDUCTING ANY HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION EVENTS.

CONNELLY ALSO FOUND THAT THE OPERATING ROD FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE COULD ALSO BE TURNED BY HAND. THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS TIGHTENED BY TURNING THE VALVE ASSEMBLY APPROXIMATELY THREE QUARTERS OF A TURN. THE COVER FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS REMOVED, THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS FOUND TO BE TIGHT AND WAS REMOVED AND THE PACKING CHECKED (FOUND TO BE OK). THE OPERATING ROD WAS TIGHTENED, THE PACKING GLAND NUT REPLACED AND TIGHTENED AND THE HOUSING REPLACED. CAR WAS SECURED AT 1320 HOURS, OCTOBER 8, 1996 AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: AS THE FREIGHT WAS BEING SORTED IT CAME DOWN THE SLIDE AND STRUCK A RETAINING BARRIER. AT THE POINT TWO OF THE FRICTION LIDS POPPED OFF AND DUMPED THE CONTENTS OF THE TWO CANS. THE SPILL WAS RECOVERED AND THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND FAXED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET. THE FLASHPOINT OF THIS MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO BE 73 DEGREE F. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. BOTH THE SHIPPER AND FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED. PATRICIA A PAUCH FROM THE PHL FAA CASFO INSPECTED THIS SHIPMENT TODAY. ONCE THE FREIGHT IS RELEASED BY THE FAA, THE SHIPPER WILL BE CALLED FOR A DISPOSITION.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS DROPPED. UPON IMPACT WITH THE CEMENT FLOOR ONE OF THE GLASS INNER BOTTLES BROKE CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE. SINCE THERE WAS NO MARKING, LABLEING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE INNER CONTENTS WERE REGULATED WE HANDLED THIS SHIPMENT THROUGH THE REGULAR SORT. ONCE WE SMELLED THE STRONG ODORS EMINATING FROM THE BOX WE REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE SORT AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO FAXED COPIES OF THE MSDS. UPON SCRUTINIZING THE MSDS WE DETERMINED THAT WE HAD JUST CAUSE TO NOTIFY THE FAA AS WE BELIEVED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. A CARGO TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM BI CHEMICALS, INC. LOCATED AT 2820 N. NORMANDY DRIVE IN PETERSBURG, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, MD.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RECEIVING FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE OF THE CARGO TANK ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA WHERE THE VEHICLE WAS PARKED.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY.  THIS MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ATTACHED SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE INDICATED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A FAULTY INTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLY. THE VALVE WAS WRAPPED IN ABSORBENT PADS AND MOVED INTO THE FACILITY'S CONTAINED RECEIVING AREA WHERE THE LADING WAS OFF-LOADED.  THE VEHICLE WAS THEN PLACED OUT OF SERVICE PENDING INSPECTION AND REPAIR BY COMPANY PERSONNEL. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO CONDUCT PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS TO IDENTIFY ANY CONDITIONS THAT COULD COMPROMISE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE PACKAGE.

RESPONDERS WERE CALLED TO A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL ON THE NORT RAMP. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS FOUND TO BE A 5 GALLON DRUM WITH A LOOSE LID.  THE LID WAS TIGHTENED AND THE MATERIAL CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN A DISPOSAL DRUM AND PUT IN THE WASTE BUILDING, AWAITING DISPOSTION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

OUR DISTRICT OFFICE HAS CONTACTED THE STATE FIRE MARSHALL OFFICE AND THEY WILL INVESTIGATE WITH A ARSON SPEC. BECAUSE OF THE DANGER INVOLVED, IF IT HAPPEN AGAIN. column168: NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER REPORT NO. 363403. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AS WELL. A WET PACKAGE CONTAINING DRY ICE WAS RECEIVED ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 2, 1996 FROM BASEL SWITZERLAND AT THE FEDEX, MERCERVILLE, NEW JERSEY, STATION. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ON FRIDAY, OCTOBER 4, 1996 THE SHIPPER REPORTED THAT IT WAS A RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE - LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL, UN2910 CONTAINING A TOTAL OF 4.2 MCI C-14. THE RECEPTIENT, FMC CORPORATION, PRINCETON, NEW JERSEY WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PICKED UP THE PACKAGE AT THE FEDEX STATION AND CONDUCTED RADIOLOGICAL SURVEYS. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF A TOTAL OF FIFTY-SIX 20 ML VIALS AND EIGHTEEN 100 ML BOTTLES WITH ACTIVITY OF 44.8 UCI C-14 IN LIQUID FORM; AND TWO VIALS OF SOLID MATERIAL WITH A TOTAL ACTIVITY OF 4.162 MCI. IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DETERMINED THAT ONE 100 ML BOTTLE HAD BROKEN, THREE 100 ML BOTTLES WERE UNCAPPED AND EMPTY, AND FOUR 20 ML VIALS WERE BROKEN. A TOTAL OF 480 ML HAD BEEN RELEASED WITHIN THE PACKAGING; BUT A VOLUME OF 235 ML CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 1.23 UCI C-14 WAS RECOVERED LEAVING APPROXIMATELY 245 ML CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 8 UCI C-14 REMAINING WITHIN THE BOX, SINCE THERE WAS NO DETECTABLE EXTERNAL CONTAMINATION EITHER ON THE OUTER SURFACES OF THE BOX OR WHERE THE BOX HAD BEEN STORED. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT APPEARS TO BE INADEQUATE PACKAGING AS OBSERVED BY FMC CORPORATION. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL PRESENT TO EITHER ABSORB SHOCK OR ABSORB SPILLED LIQUID. THE VIALS HAD BEEN PLACED IN BOXES WITH CARDBOARD DIVIDERS, BUT THE LARGER BOTTLES APPEARED TO BE LOOSE. SEE REPORT 96110201A

A WET PACKAGE CONTAINING DRY ICE WAS RECEIVED ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 2, 1996 FROM BASEL SWITZERLAND AT THE FEDEX, MERCERVILLE, NEW JERSEY, STATION. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ON FRIDAY, OCTOBER 4, 1996 THE SHIPPER REPORTED THAT IT WAS A RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE - LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL, UN2910 CONTAINING A TOTAL OF 4.2 MCI C-14. THE RECEPTIENT, FMC CORPORATION, PRINCETON, NEW JERSEY WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PICKED UP THE PACKAGE AT THE FEDEX STATION AND CONDUCTED RADIOLOGICAL SURVEYS. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF A TOTAL OF FIFTY-SIX 20 ML VIALS AND EIGHTEEN 100 ML BOTTLES WITH ACTIVITY OF 44.8 UCI C-14 IN LIQUID FORM; AND TWO VIALS OF SOLID MATERIAL WITH A TOTAL ACTIVITY OF 4.162 MCI. IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DETERMINED THAT ONE 100 ML BOTTLE HAD BROKEN, THREE 100 ML BOTTLES WERE UNCAPPED AND EMPTY, AND FOUR 20 ML VIALS WERE BROKEN. A TOTAL OF 480 ML HAD BEEN RELEASED WITHIN THE PACKAGING; BUT A VOLUME OF 235 ML CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 1.23 UCI C-14 WAS RECOVERED LEAVING APPROXIMATELY 245 ML CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 8 UCI C-14 REMAINING WITHIN THE BOX, SINCE THERE WAS NO DETECTABLE EXTERNAL CONTAMINATION EITHER ON THE OUTER SURFACES OF THE BOX OR WHERE THE BOX HAD BEEN STORED. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT APPEARS TO BE INADEQUATE PACKAGING AS OBSERVED BY FMC CORPORATION. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL PRESENT TO EITHER ABSORB SHOCK OR ABSORB SPILLED LIQUID. THE VIALS HAD BEEN PLACED IN BOXES WITH CARDBOARD DIVIDERS, BUT THE LARGER BOTTLES APPEARED TO BE LOOSE. SEE REPORT 96110201A

column42: DYES, LIQUID, TOXIC, N.O.S. OR DYE INTERMEDIATES, LIQUID, TOXIC, N.O.S.
column168: LIQUID WAS FOUND ON TOP OF TOTE WHEN TRAILER WAS UNLOADED.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DRIVER NOTICED STRONG SMELL COMING FROM REAR PUP AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. WE OPENED TRAILER TO INVESTIGATE, AND NOTICED DARK OR MOIST CARDBOARD UNDER ONE DRUM, PULLED UP TO DOCK AND REMOVED DRUM. LOOKED FOR ANY SIGNS OF LEAKING, PUT ON SIDE AND LEAKING STOPPED. RESEALED TRAILER AND NOTATED ON TRAVEL COPY & MANIFEST THAT ONE DRUM WAS HELD AT TERMINAL DUE TO LEAKING. COULD FIND NO SIGNS OF PUNCTURE OF ANY TYPE ON DRUM. APPEARS LEAK IS COMING FROM IN BETWEEN DRUM CAP & BARREL OF DRUM WHERE THE TWO PIECES CONNECT.

WHEN DRIVER MADE DELIVERY, THE DAMAGE WAS NOTICED. DRIVER SAID THAT THE 25LB BAGS SEEM TO BE HANGING OFF OF THE PALLET. HE ALSO SAID THAT TOO MANY BAGS WERE ON PALLET. CONSTANT HANDLING OF OVER LOADED PALLET CAUSED THE DAMAGE. DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSITION AND GENERAL CLEANUP WAS DONE.

WE REMOVED FROM THE DOCK THE DRUM DOLLY THAT PUNCTURED THE DRUM AND HAVE ORDERED A REPLACEMENT DRUM DOLLY TO MOVE FUTURE PLASTIC DRUMS SO THAT WE CAN PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING. NOT SURE WHY THE DRUM DOLLY DID THIS BUT THE SPILLAGE WAS MINOR BECAUSE WE WERE ABLE TO KEEP THE DRUM DOLLY INSIDE THE DRUM AND GET IT TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT A MAJOR INCIDENT.

CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANKS ARE LOCATED AT GROUND LEVEL DUE TO CONSTRUCTION. DOME CAP ON STORAGE TANK IS OPEN TO VENT TANK BECAUSE OF REPAIR TO VENTING SYSTEMS. CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADER MAKES HOOK UP AND CHECKS TANKS. HE NEVER ADVISED THE DRIVER OF OVERFLOWING UNTIL CARGO TANK WENT EMPTY. UNLOADER STATED PRODUCT STAYED CONTAINED IN TANK AREA.

THE PLASTIC DRUM WAS LOADED ON THE FLOOR AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. A PROTRUDING BOLT IN THE BOTTOM OF THE OVERHEAD DOOR CHAFED A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND POSITIONED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING A DRUM AT INTEL, DRUM DOLLY PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF AN ASHLAND DRUM. DRUM WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE. SPILL WAS APPROPRIATELY CLEANED UP. WILL CHECK TO SEE IF WE WANT TO ROUND OFF EDGES OR LOOK AT DIFFERENT WAYS TO UNLOAD TRUCK. ASHLAND IS CONSIDERING NEW DRUM.

column168: LID TO METAL PAINT CAN WAS NOT HELD SECURELY IN PLACE BY POSITIVE MEANS AND CAME COMPLETELY OFF THE CAN AND LEAKED INSIDE A CESSNA 208 AIRCRAFT NUMBER 756F. THE PLANE WAS ON THE GROUND AND WAS UNLOADING WHEN THE SPILL WAS NOTICED. THE AIRCRAGT WAS CLEANED AND INSPECTED BY NOLAND DECOTO FLOYING SERVICE IN YAKIMA. MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET PROVIDED BY SHIPPER INDICATES THAT THE FLASH POINT IS 105 DEGREES. FAA NOTIFIED AND REMAINING PAINT WILL BE DISPOSED OF UPON RELEASE.

DURING THE SORT, THE DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF TOLUENE FROM ITS CAP. UPON CLOSE SCRUNTIZATION WE FOUND THAT THE CAP WAS NOT TIGHT. THE CAP WAS SECURED, THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS WIPED UP, AND TO ENSURE THIS DID NOT CAUSE ANY FURTHER DOWN TIME, THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND MOVED TO THE RECIPIENT AT THE SHIPPER REQUEST.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DURING THE SORT THE BOXES WERE DROPPED. PAINT BEGAN SEEPING OUT OF THE BOX. UPON OPENING THE BOXES AFTER CLEANING UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL, WE DETERMINED THAT THE FRICTION LIDS POPPED OFF BECAUSE THERE WAS NO POSITIVE CLOSURE. THERE WERE NO CAN CLIPS OR RING-LOC ON THE LIDS. THIS IS A HIDDEN DISCREPANCY AND REQUIRED TO BE REPORTED UNDER 49CFR 173.31. THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED THAT THE FREIGHT BE RETURNED TO THEM.

DURING THE OCEAN TRANSIT ONE PAIL WAS DISLODGE FROM THE PALLET SHRINK WRAP AND WAS PINCHED BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE OCEAN BOX WALL. SIMILAR PALLETS IN THE OCEAN SHIPMENT SHOWED NO ISSUES. WE WILL BE REVIEWING THE STRETCH WRAP QUALITY AS A POSSIBLE CAUSE. THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED BY EMTECH AND THE RESIDUES WAS INCINERATED.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: SPILL RESPONDER WERE CALLED TO A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS FOUND THAT A STRONG ODOR WAS EMITTING FROM A PACKAGE. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE. PACKAGE WAS PUT IN A DISPOSAL DRUM AND PLACED IN THE WASTE BUILDING AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

CARGO TANKER WAS LOADING - RUBBER FLEXIBLE HOSE TRANSFERRING LIQUID TO THE CARGO TANK TANK DEVELOPED A PIN HOLE LEAK AND SOMETHING LESS THAN A PINT OF MATERIAL WAS DISCHARGED TO THE GROUND. MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY AETS AND MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL AT A PERMITTED FACILITY.

OUR EMPLOYEES WERE ATTEMPTING TO LEVEL A 4000 GAL TANK AT THE MIDNIGHT ROSE CASINO IN CRIPPLE CREEK PRIOR TO FILLING IT. THE TANK WAS AT 50 %. WHILE PERFORMING THIS TASK, THE VAPOR LINE BROKE AND THERE WAS A MAJOR, UNCONTROLLED RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE. THE VAPOR LINE BROKE BETWEEN THE SHUT-OFF VALVE AND TANK. DISTRICT MANAGER REPORTED THAT THE INCIDENT OCCURED ABOUT 11:15 AM AND WITHIN 5 MIN. THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED. WITHIN 2 MIN THE FIRE DEPT. WAS ON THE SCENE. TOTAL EVACUATION TIME WAS 11:30 TO 3:09 PM. THE PEOPLE WERE ASKED TO STAY IN THE BUSINESS AND NO OTHERS WERE ALLOWED IN THE AREA FOR PUBLIC TRAVEL. THE TANK WAS ALLOWED TO RELEASE SO THAT A NEW VALVE COULD BE PLACED ON THE TANK.

A VAN WATERS & ROGERS TRUCK WAS DRIVING SOUTH ON I-17 FROM CAMP VERDE, AZ. TO VAN WATERS & ROGERS PHOENIX, AZ. WHEN THE TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE PHOENIX FACILITY WE DISCOVERED THAT A DRUM OF HAZARDOUS WASTE HAD BEEN LEAKING. THIS LEAK OCCURRED SOMEWHERE BETWEEN CAMP VERDE AND PHOENIX, THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN THE TRAILER AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF THE SPILL ON THE ROAD. NOTE: THE DRIVERS CHECK STOP IN CAMP VERDE, AZ THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAKING CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER LEAKED PRODUCT SOMEWHERE BETWEEN CAMP VERDE, AZ AND PHOENIX, AZ.

FOUR DRUMS WERE PLACED ON PALLET AND SHRINKWRAPPED. DURING TRANSPORT, THE DRUMS SHIFTED AND ONE OF THE DRUMS FELL HALFWAY OFF OF THE PALLET, AT THE EDGE OF THE PALLET. THE SHIFTING OF THE DRUM AGAINST THE EDGE OF THE PALLET, CAUSED TWO HOLES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AT TWO ENDS. THE DRIVER PUT THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE, THINKING HE HAD STOPPED THE LEAK, BUT DID NOT REALIZE THERE WAS ANOTHER HOLE. THE ENTIRE 55 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT LEAKED OUT INTO THE TRL. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND MSDS SHEETS FAXED. THE SHIPPER INFORMED ME THAT WATER NEUTRALIZES THE CORROSIVE ACTIONS, SO THAT SMALL RUNOFFS WERE NOT A PROBLEM. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH OIL DRY, AND STOPPED ALL RUN OFFS. THE TRL WAS CLEANED APPROPRIATELY.

column168: I ARRIVED AT CAR ON 2 LEAD AT 0730. I PLACED FIVE GALLON BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK AND WENT TO TOP OF CAR AND TRIED TO CLOSE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. I COULD NOT MAKE IT ANY TIGHTER. I WENT BACK TO THE BOTTOM AND TRIED TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WITH A 36" PIPE WRENCH, BUT COULD NOT MOVE IT. I THEN REMOVED THE PLUG FROM 1 1/2" VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTLET CAP. I OPENED THE VALVE TO MAKE SURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED; IT WAS NOT. I CLOSED 1 1/2" VALVE, WENT BACK TO THE TOP AND OPENED AND CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO TRY AND REMOVE ANYTHING THAT MIGHT BE CAUGHT IN THE VALVE SEAT. THIS WAS DONE THREE TIMES. AT 0830 IT WAS DECIDED TO ISOLATE THE CAR AND CALL CHEMTREC. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO IC STRAIGHT TRACK AND CONTAINERS WERE PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CATCH THE LEAKING PRODUCT. THE BUCKET WAS THEN REMOVED. EI DUPONT RESPONSE TRUCK ARRIVED AT 1650, WORKED ON THE CAR UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 2030. BECAUSE RAIN AND WATER COULD NOT GET INTO THE PRODUCT, IT WAS DECIDED TO STOP UNTIL 0600, OCTOBER 28, 1996. PRODUCT FROM DUPX 20083 WAS PUMPED INTO GATX 80451. THE CATCH WERE PUMPED INTO GATX 80455.

THE PLASTIC DRUM BROKE FREE FROM THE BLOCKING AND BRACING INSIDE THE VEHICLE. COURIER BEGAN HEARING A THUMPING SOUND IN THE BACK OF THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER ALSO NOTICED AN ODOR ABOUT THIS TIME. THE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND INSPECTED THE FREIGHT. WHEN HE UPRIGHTED AN SECURED THE DRUM, HE GOT SOME OF THE CONTENTS ON HIS CLOTHES AND HANDS. BECAUSE HE WAS CLOSED TO THE STATION, THE DRIVE DECIDED TO DRIVE ON TO THE STATION. UPON ARRIVAL, HE COMPLAINED OF BURNING EYES AND DIFFICULTY BREATHING. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE CALLED TO RESPOND AT THIS TIME. THE DRUM WAS NOT DROPPED, IT SIMPLY TURNED OVER INSIDE THE VEHICLE. CONTENTS LEAKED FROM THE TOP CLOSURE WHEN THE TOP CAME LOOSE. EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED BY THE EMTS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND LATER RELEASED. THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP FROM THE VAN AND EVERYTHING PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER THE NEXT DAY.

OUR DRIVER STOPPED FOR A SLIGHT MECHANICAL PROBLEM WITH HIS TRACTOR.  AN EMPLOYEE OF THE TOLL ROAD AUTHORITY STOPPED TO SEE IF HE COULD ASSIST. THE STATE EMPLOYEE SMELLED A STRANGE ODOR.  BOTH OUR DRIVER AND THE STATE EMPLOYEE NOTICED A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD DRAINED DOWN THE DRIP TUBE AND A SMALL SPOT ON THE CHASSIS.  OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PULL ON TO AN AREA HE COULD GET OFF THE ROADWAY AND WAIT FOR THE STATE POLICE.  WHEN THE POLICE ARRIVED THEY CALLED FOR THE EMERGENCY HELP TEAM FROM THE SHIPPER (RHONE-POULENC).  WHEN THE HELP TEAM ARRIVED THEY FOUND THAT THE LUGS ON THE DOME LID WERE LOOSE.  THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED, AND OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE CUSTOMER FOR DELIVERY.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF THE EVENT:  TANK CAR WAS BEING "PADDED" WITH NITROGEN IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING TO STORAGE.  THE TANK CAR RUPTURE DISC FAILED WHEN THE NITROGEN PRESSURE REGULATOR FAILED. IMMEDIATE ACTION:  THE NITROGEN SUPPLY WAS "VALVED OFF" AND THE TANK CAR RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED. BASIC CAUSE:  UPON INVESTIGATION, THE NITROGEN PRESSURE REGULATOR FAILED CAUSING THE TANK CAR TO OVER PRESSURE.  THE PRESSURE REGULATOR WAS REPLACED.
FITTING POPPED OUT OF GROUND.

column168: DRIVER BACKED INTO DOCK AT NAVISTAR WHICH IS A HAZARD CONTAINED AREA WITH HOLD TANK.  RECEIVER OPENED REAR DOOR TO FIND FLUID RUNNING OUT OF BACK OF TRAILER INTO CONTAINED AREA.  COMPANY HAZMAT TEAM (NAVISTAR) TOOK CHARGE OF OPERATION.  ON MY FURTHER INVESTIGATION, REAR TRAILER LOAD OF FOUR TOTES AND 25 DRUMS SHIFTED FORWARD 8 FEET, RIPPING LOAD BAR FROM SIDES AND RAMMING DRUMS IN NOSE OF TRAILER, PUTTING HOLE IN ONE DRUM OF SANTICIZER 160, CAUSING LEAK.  DRIVER DID PERFORM EMERGENCY STOP TO AVOID POLICE CAR WITH EMERGENCY LIGHTS AT INTERSECTION OF DARROW RD. AND GILCHRIST RD. IN AKRON, OH AT 4;00AM.  DID NOT DISCOVER LEAK UNTIL ARRIVING AT COLUMBUS, OHIO.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: AFTER PLACEMENT FOR UNLOADING CAR WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PAST OUTLET CAP.  CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER CAR TO CATCH PRODUCT.  NO EXTERNAL VALVE WAS ON CAR, CAP WAS LOOSENED SLOWLY, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT INTERNAL VALVE WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO DRIP PAST.  ALSO GASKET IN SEAL CAP WAS TORN AND DEFORMED.  EXTERNAL WAS INSTALLED AND PRODUCT OFF LOADED. NOTIFICATION REQUIREMENTS WERE COMPLETED, PRODUCT LOSS DETERMINED, AND CLEAN-UP PERFORMED.  WASTE IS TEMP. BEING STORED AT SITE AWAITING PICK-UP BY DISPOSAL FACILITY.  RECOMMEND THE RAILCARS HAVE TO BE EQUIPPED WITH BOTH INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES.  ALSO CLOSER INSPECTION OF CAR BY SHIPPER WITH ATTENTION TO INSTALLATION OF GASKET ECT.

CUSTOMER AGENT SAID VALVES WERE OPEN FOR RECEIVING.  DRIVER TURNED ON PUMP, AND THEN WENT TO REAR OF TRACTOR.  HE HEARD THE PUMP CAVITATING, BUT BEFORE HE COULD MOVE, HE HOSE BURST AND HE WAS SPRAYED WITH PRODUCT.  HE SHUT OFF THE VALVES AT REAR OF TRAILER.  THE CUSTOMER PERSONNEL RUSHED HIM TO THE EMERGENCY SHOWER AND RINSED HIM FOR 40 MINUTES.  HE WAS GIVEN DRY CLOTHING AND WAS NOT IN NEED OF ANY FURTHER TREATMENT.  HE DROVE HIS TRUCK BACK TO HIS ASSIGNED TERMINAL AT PEDRICKTOWN, NJ AFTER A DIFFERENT DRIVER WAS SENT IN TO PUMP OFF THE PRODUCT AT THE CUSTOMER.  PRIOR TO STARTING THE PUMP, DRIVER HAD INSPECTED HOSES AND FOUND THEM TO BE APPARENTLY FREE OF DEFECTS.  HE FEELS THAT A VALVE ON CUSTOMER SYSTEM HAD NOT BEEN OPENED FULLY.

THE TRAILER WAS GOING TO BE BROKEN WHEN THE DOCKMAN CLAIMED HE SMELLED SOMETHING COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED ON THE YARD AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED.  THE CREW INSPECTED THE CYLINDERS AND DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE VALVES HAD WORKED ITSELF LOOSE. THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CYLINDERS WERE SHIPPED.

CARGO TANK WAS PARKED ON AN INCLINE WHILE LOADING.  THE CARGO TANK WAS EQUIPPED WITH BOTH A SIDE AND FRONT CARGO TANK MOUNTED LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE FOR SAFE LOADING WHILE PARKED ON AN INCLINE.  DRIVER MONITORED ONLY THE FRONT TANK GAUGE DURING THE LOADING PROCESS WHICH REFLECTED A SMALLER LOADED VOLUME AS COMPARED TO THE ACTUAL LOADED VOLUME ALLOWING THE TANK TO OVERFLOW. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BIOREMEDIATED ON SITE. DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED THAT DURING A LOADING OPERATION WITH A CARGO TANK PARKED ON AN INCLINE THAT SPECIAL CARE SHOULD BE GIVEN TO MONITORING EACH LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE AND THE EFFECT OF THE CARGO TANK INCLINE ON THE GAUGES.

column168: GATX 32932 WAS DISPLAYING SLIGHT SEEPAGE COMING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WHILE STANDING IN BATTLE CREEK YARD. THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED. ADJUSTMENT WAS MADE TO THE OPERATING SHAFT, CORRECTING SEEPAGE. CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. SHIPPER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE CAR AT THE TIME OF LOADING AND ALSO NEGLECTED TO FOLLOW RECOMMENDED LOADING PROCEDURE FOR GENERAL SERVICE TANK CARS EQUIPPED WITH BOTTOM OUTLETS BY FAILING TO LEAVE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP OFF DURING LOADING.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HOURS, MONDAY, OCTOBER 28, 1996, A CONRAIL YARD CREW DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR ORIGINATING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR SAZX 21485 CONTAINING NITRATING ACID MIXTURES. APPROXIMATE NOTIFICATION MADE. CONRAIL MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICES AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE TANK CAR CORPORATION OF AMERICA ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. INVESTIGATION REVEALED A CORRODED MANWAY NOZZLE IN AREA WHERE IT MEETS THE MANWAY COVER PLATE ON THE LEFT SIDE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY APPLYING TEFLON PACKING IN THE GAP CAUSED BY CORROSION (AN APPROXIMATE 4"-5" LENGTH AREA). DUCT TAPES WAS APPLIED AROUND THE ENTIRE CIRCUMFERENCE OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE/COVER PLATE TO INSURE THE SECUREMENT OF THE PACKING. AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, OCTOBER 28, 1996, THE CAR WAS SECURED AND OKAYED TO BE TRANSPORTED TO THE TANK CAR CORPORATION OF AMERICA FOR REPAIR.

EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHEN HE NOTICED THE SMELL OF PRODUCT. DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF CLIMBING GRIFFEN ROAD WHEN HE NOTICED FUEL COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF THE ROAD. CLIFF BERRY, INC WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 350 GALLONS OF JET A FUEL.
1 DRUM WAS CREASED BY A FORK LIFT CLAMP WHEN THE DRUMS WERE LOADED, CAUSING A SMALL LEAK.

DURING THE DELIVERY AT HUNTSMAN CORPORATION AS THE DRIVERS WERE PRESSURING UP THE TRAILER FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER, THE SAFETY RELIEF SYSTEM RUPTURE DISC FAILED PREMATURELY WHICH RESULTED IN IGNITION OF THE VENTING GAS. THE DRIVERS QUICKLY ACTIVATED THE VENT SYSTEM FIRE ABATEMENT SYSTEM AND EXTINGUISHED THE FLAME, ALLOWED THE VENTING PRESSURE TO REDUCE AND THEN SWITCHED TO THE SECONDARY RELIEF SYSTEM AND THEN CONTINUED THEIR PRODUCT DELIVERY WITHOUT ANY FURTHER INCIDENT. THE PRIMARY RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED UPON RETURN TO THE NEW ORLEANS TERMINAL.

WHILE ENROUTE FROM NEW ORLEANS TO MACINTOSH, ALABAMA, (NEAR MOBILE, ALABAMA) THE DRIVER NOTICED VENTING FROM THE TRAILER VENT STACK. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE VEHICLE IN A SAFE LOCATION AND INVESTIGATED THE CAUSE OF THE VENTING. THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE VENT VALVE HAD OPENED SLIGHTLY AND HE CLOSED THE VALVE TIGHTLY. THE VENTING WAS STOPPED AT THIS TIME AND THE DRIVER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO HIS SUPERVISOR AND CONTINUED ON HIS WAY. ** UPON RETURN TO NEW ORLEANS, AN INSPECTION AND INVESTIGATION INDICATED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF ICE FROM PRE-TRIP EQUILIBRATION HAD MOST LIKELY PREVENTED FULL CLOSURE OF THE VENT VALVE AND WHEN THE ICE MELTED, THE VENT OPENED SLIGHTLY, RESULTING IN THE VENTING.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0050 HOURS, MONDAY, OCTOBER 25, 1996, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR DUPX 20083 CONTAINING N, N-DIMETHYL FORMAMIDE LEAKING. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0130 HOURS, CONRAIL MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICES AND CAR DEPARTMENT GENERAL FOREMAN ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE PACKING NUT WAS NOT SUFFICIENTLY TIGHT TO KEEP THE OPERATING ROD FROM BECOMING LOOSE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY PARTIALLY TURNING THE ROD WITHOUT LOOSENING THE PACKING NUT. THE NUT WAS TIGHTENED AFTER FIRST LOOSENING THE NUT THEN TIGHTENING THE ROD AND RETIGHTENED THE NUT. AT APPROXIMATELY 0220 HOURS, OCTOBER 25, 1996, THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

EMPLOYEE DELIVERED 220 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL #2 TO THE INCORRECT PIPE AT THE CUSTOMERS HOME. OIL WENT DIRECTLY INTO THE BASEMENT OF CUSTOMERS HOME. SUMP PUMP AUTOMATICALLY CAME ON AND PUMPED THE FUEL INTO SEWER SYSTEM. THIS WAS THE FIRST DELIVERY TO THIS CUSTOMERS HOME AND WAS PROBABLY A COMMUNICATION PROBLEM BETWEEN CUSTOMER AND DRIVER. ACTION TAKEN: CITY, STATE, COUNTY, AND FEDERAL OFFICALS WERE NOTIFIED. SEWER SYSTEM IS A SELF CONTAINED CONTAINER. THE OIL WAS CONFINED TO CONTAINER. A TRUCK WAS SENT INTO PUMP OFF FUEL OIL OUT OF SEWER SYSTEM. OIL CAUSED A SHORT IN CIRCUIT BOARD OF LIFT PUMP, PUMP WILL BE REPAIRED. REPAIRS ARE UNDERWAY AT THIS TIME. THE CUSTOMER HOME: A COMPANY BY THE NAME OF SERV PRO HAD BEEN HIRED AND THEY HAVE PUMPED OZONE TREATMENT INTO THE HOME TO HELP REMOVE SMELL, THIS PROCESS WILL BE REPEATED IF NECESSARY. THEY HAVE PUT FLOOR DRY DOWN ONTO CONCRETE FLOOR TO ABSORB OIL AND ALSO BANKED IT UP THE WALLS. CLEAN UP TO CUSTOMERS HOME IS IN PROCESS AT THIS TIME ALSO.

column168: PUMP LEAKED AT PACKING DURING UNLOADING PROCESS.
CUSTOMER OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM AND CENTRAL TRANSPORT OVERFLOWED CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CSE SERVICE CENTER LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED. AT THAT TIME WE OBTAINED THE BILL OF LADING AND UNLOADED DOWN TO THE PLASTIC TOTE TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS LEAKING AND WHAT MIGHT HAVE CAUSED THE LEAKAGE. AFTER THOROUGH RESEARCH WE DISCOVERED THAT THE MAIN CAP ON THE TOTE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AND LIQUID HAD SPLASHED OUT DURING TRANSPORTATION. WE USED ABSORBAL TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED LIQUID CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO OBTAIN AUTHORIZATION TO CUT THE SEAL AND TIGHTEN THE CAP. ALL OF THE SPILLAGE AND ABSORBAL WAS PLACED IN A 30 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL CONTACT PROPER AUTHORITY FOR PROPER DISPOSITION OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND CONTAINMENT MATERIAL. LID WAS SECURED AND REST OF FREIGHT MOVED TO DESTINATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, FRIDAY, OCTOBER 11, 1996, A CONRAIL CONDUCTOR DISCOVERED VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX30155 CONTAINING POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION AT FMC PLANT.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REPLACING THE DISC.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, OCTOBER 11, 1996, THE CAR WAS SECURED.

column168: ON OCTOBER 7, 1996, OVAC, INC. WAS REQUESTED BY THE LOUISIANA DEQ TO RESPOND TO A TRAILER PARKED IN A SHOPPING CENTER PARKING LOT.  THE TRAILER WAS RELEASING A WHITISH VAPOR CLOUD.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS STRIKE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED.  NEIL CLARK ARRIVED ON SITE WITHIN 5 MINUTES AND BEGAN AN INITIAL INVESTIGATION OF THE SITUATION.  ICS WAS SET UP AND APPROPRIATE SITE SAFETY HEALTH PLANS WERE COMPLETED.  ONCE MEDICAL MONITORING WAS COMPLETE OUR ENTRY TEAM ACCESSED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND 3 OF THE 6 BOLTS ON THE DOME COVER WERE LOOSE AND NOT ATTACHED PROPERLY.  OVAC, INC.'S MOVED THE TRAILER AND THEIR PROPERTY TO A SECURE STORAGE LOCATION UNTIL THE OWNERS WERE LOCATED.  OVAC'S ACTIVITIES TOOK APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS FROM START TO FINISH.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM PUBLIC SERVICE ELECTRIC AND GAS LOCATED AT 472 WESTON CANAL ROAD IN FRANKLIN TOWNSHIP, NJ TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC.  LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RECEIVING FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAP OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDY DRI.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER IDENTIFIED THAT THE GASKET USED TO CREATE A SEAL BETWEEN THE DRUM AND THE TOP BUNG WAS DEFECTIVE.  A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE CONTAINER WAS RECEIVED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING DISPOSAL.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  ********* PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER TO INSURE THAT ALL CLOSURES AND RELATED COMPONENTS ARE IN PLACE AND SECURE PRIOR TO TRANSPORT.

column42: POTASSIUM NITRATE AND SODIUM NITRITE MIXTURES
column168: OUR TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT WHICH CAUSED THE TRAILER TO TURN TO ITS SIDE.  THE IMPACT CAUSED THE TOP OF THE TRAILER TO BREAK OPEN CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO SPILL OUT ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  THERE WERE A TOTAL OF 8 PALLETS EACH CONTAINING 25 100LB BAGS OF POTASSIUM NITRATE AND SODIUM NITRITE MIXTURES.  THERE WERE 102 BAGS WHICH WERE TORN.  APPROX. 2000LBS OF MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ON A GENTLEMAN'S FARM.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST OUT OF BIRMINGHAM ALABAMA RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  THE MATERIAL WAS ALSO CONSIDERED A TYPE OF FERTILIZER.  MISSISSIPPI'S DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS NOTIFIED AND OK'D THE SPREAD OF THIS MATERIAL OVER THE FARMERS LAND.  WE DID GET PERMISSION FROM THE LANDOWNER TO PROCEED.  THE MATERIAL WAS PUT INTO A SPREADER AND WAS SPREAD OVER HIS LAND, AND THEN A TRACTOR TILLED OVER THE MATERIAL.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROX. 1130 HOURS, TUESDAY, OCTOBER 29, 1996, DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, A CONRAIL MANAGER HAZMAT FIELD SERVICES AND TRAINMASTER, NOTED TANK CAR SAZX 30097, RESIDUE LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS, WIH AUDIBLE LEAK FROM "B" LIQUID VALVE.  SOAPY WATER APPLIED, INDICATING LEAK AT THREADS OF CLOSURE PLUG, AND THREADED BUSHING AT THE VALVE OPENING.  TANK CAR CORP. OF AMERICA(TCCA), ORELAND, PA SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO INSPECT.  HE USED A WRENCH ON THE OPERATING HANDWHEEL TO ASSIST WITH SECUREMENT OF THE VALVE. THE CLOSURE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO THE THREADS. CLOSURE PLUG REAPPLIED AND SECURED.  NO DICERNBLE LEAK WAS DETECTED FROM THE CLOSURE PLUG AREA AS NOTED BEFORE.  LIQUID TEFLON WAS APPLIED TO THE BUSHING'S THREADS TO TEMPORARILY SECURE THE LEAK.  CAR OKAYED TO BE SWITCHED TO TCCA FOR VALVE REPAIR/REPLACEMENT.

NO OBVIOUS SOURCE OF LEAKAGE COULD BE DETECTED.  IT IS BELIEVED THE VAPOR MAY HAVE COME FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD AND OBSERVED. WHEN EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE WAS FOUND THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND PICKED THAT EVENING TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: AT NEW ORLEANS, LA, A CITIZEN REPORTED TO THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT THAT HE COULD SMELL AN ODOR COMING FROM THE DIRECTION OF A TANK CAR THAT WAS SITTING ON NEARBY INTERCHANGE TRACK.  THE FIRE DEPT RESPONDED.  CSXT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR, ED ERNEWEIN RESPONDED ON BEHALF OF CSXT.  THE FIRE DEPT DETERMINED THE CAR WAS LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  SHELL CHEMICAL THE LOADER OF THE CAR RESPONDED, ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE LEAK BUT COULD NOT. SHELL PUT A "MIDLAND" KIT OVER THE SAFETY VALVE & STOPPED THE LEAK.  AN EMERGENCY APPROVAL WAS OBTAINED FROM THE FRA TO MOVE THE CAR BACK TO SHELL AT NORCO, LA.  SHELL UNLOADED THE CAR, PURGED IT WITH NITROGEN & IS SENDING IT TO BEAUMOUNT, TX FOR REPAIRS.

column168: DRIVER STATED THAT THE NOSE OF HIS CARGO TANK MUST HAVE BEEN LOWER THAN THE REAR OF THE TANK WHERE THE VALVE IS LOCATED.  HE FINISHED UNLOADING AND PUT AWAY HIS HOSES BUT FORGOT TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  WHEN HE MOVED FORWARD THE NOSE OF THE TANK CAME UP AND THERE WAS SOME PRODUCT LEFT IN THE TANK AND IT CAME OUT THE BACK VALVE.  HE STOPPED THE TRUCK AND RAN BACK TO THE REAR AREA OF THE TANK BUT COULDN'T GET CLOSE TO THE VALVE BECAUSE OF THE FUMES.  HE PANICKED AND FORGOT ABOUT THE REMOTE SHUT-OFF DEVICE ON THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  WHEN THE PRODUCT HAD RUN OUT, HE CLOSED THE VALVE AND LEFT THE SCENE NOT INFORMING THE CUSTOMER OR OUR COMPANY.  HE HAD RECEIVED TRAINING AND WRITTEN INSTRUCTIONS WITH THE LAST 30 DAYS TO REPORT THE SPILL IMMEDIATELY TO OUR SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  SPILL CLEANED UP BY PRIVATE CONTRACTOR AND APPROVED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC HEALTH IN MERCED, CA.

IT STRUCK SEVERAL TREES AND CAME TO REST ON IT'S SIDE FACING WEST.  THE CARGO SPILLED OUT THROUGH THE ROOF OF THE CARGO BOX. THE VEHICLE CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PRIMARILY HOSPITAL SUPPLIES. THE DRIVER SUSTAINED PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO HIS KNEE CAP AND WAS HOSPITALIZED FOR FURTHER EXAMINATION OF HIS ABDOMINAL AREA.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO INTERNAL INJURIES EXISTED.  THE INJURY SUSTAINED WAS SOLELY FROM THE IMPACT OF THE VEHICLE, AND UNRELATED TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE.

column168: CAUSE OF THE SPILL - DRIVER ERROR - OPEN VALVE. PRODUCT BEING LOADED WENT THROUGH THE OPEN VALVE INTO A HOSE. THE HOSE WAS IN THE TRAILER HOSE RACK, AND WAS NOT CAPPED. THE FUEL SPRAYED OUT OF THE HOSE ACROSS THE CURBING IN THE CENTER CIRCLE AREA TO THE NORTH OF THE LOADING RACK AREA. THE FUEL ASO RAN OUT OF THE HOSE RACK, ONTO THE PAVEMENT. AFTER FLOODING THE DRAIN, THE SPILLING PRODUCT BACKED UP ALONG THE CURB (ON THE PAVEMENT). DRIVER DID NOT SEE THE SPILL UNTIL PRODUCT HAD BACKED UP BY THE DRIVER KIOSK. 771 GALLONS WERE SPILLED. 600 GALLONS WENT INTO THE OIL/WATER SEPARATOR AND 171 GALLONS ONTO THE GROUND.

column168: CARGO VAN TRUCK T-234 WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-85, RETURNING TO THE P.E.I. MAGAZINE SITE. AS HE CRESTED A HILL NEAR EXIT 63 HE REALIZED CARS WERE STOPPED IN BOTH NORTHBOUND LANES ABOUT 125 FEET IN FRONT OF HIM.  TRAFFIC WAS BACKED UP BECAUSE OF LINE PAINTING.  HE HIT THE BRAKES, LOCKING DOWN THE REAR WHEELS.  HE RELEASED THE BRAKES AND TRIED TO SLIP AROUND THE GUARDRAIL ONTO THE GRASS MEDIAN.  THE BACK END OF THE CARGO BOX CLIPPED THE GUARDRAIL SENDING THE TRUCK DOWN THE MEDIAN SIDEWAYS. WITH THE TRUCK SLOWING DOWN, HE TRIED TO STRAIGHTEN IT OUT BUT IT FLIPPED ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE WITH PART OF THE CARGO BOX IN THE LEFT LANE OF SOUTHBOUND TRAFFIC.  AN ONCOMING CAR HIT THE CARGO BOX.  DRIVER WAS IMMEDIATELY DRUG/ALCOHOL TESTED.  DRIVER WAS ISSUED A WRITTEN WARNING AND WAS MADE TO ATTEND A DEFENSIVE DRIVING COURSE.

RADIATION PROTECTION PERSONNEL DISCOVERED TOP OF CONTAINER IMPROPERLY SECURED. MINOR CONTAMINATION OF OUR  TRUCK WAS ADDRESSED BY THEM AND THEN RELEASED TO US. PACKAGE SPECIFICS AND QUESTIONS SHOULD BE REFERRED TO:  RICHARD KERR 815-458-2147 EXT. 2146 COMMONWEALTH EDISON BRAIDWOOD FACILITY.

column168: AS TRUCK STOPPED TO PAY TOLL, A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT OF PIPE LEADING FROM RUPTURE DISK.  WE BELIEVE THE RUPTURE DISK FAILED DUE TO "SLOPPING" OF PRODUCT. AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED.  MDE OVERSAW CLEANUP AT SCENE.  MINIMAL LOSS AND NO DAMAGE TO PROPERTY.  RUPTURE DISKS SHOULD BE REPLACED WITH SELF CLOSING PRESSURE RELIEF VALVES.

THE RELEASE OCCURRED DUE TO LEAK ON THE BOTTOM VALVE OF A RAILCAR. THE RAILCAR HAD RECENTLY HAD A NEW INNER LINER INSTALLED AT A FACILITY IN TEXAS, PRIOR TO BEING SENT TO KCI.  AT THE TIME OF RELEASE, THE RAILCAR WAS BEING LOADED WITH PRODUCT PHENOL FOR THE FIRST TIME FOLLOWING THE RELINING PROCEDURE.  WHEN THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED, THE LOADING WAS SHUTDOWN.  THE RAILCAR CONTENTS (APPROXIMATELY 25,00O# PHENOL) WAS THEN PUMPED TO A RECYCLE TANK.  DURING THIS TIME, AN ESTIMATED 60 GALLONS OF PHENOL ESCAPED FROM THE LEAK POINT ONTO A FULLY CONTAINED CONCRETE AREA.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS TREATED IN KCI'S ONSITE BIOLOGICAL OXIDATION WASTEWATER TREATMENT FACILITY.  THE RAILCAR BOTTOMS VALVE WAS LATER INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE A DAMAGED GASKET AT THE SEAL FOR THE BOTTOM SUPPORT RING OF THE VALVE MECHANISM.  THIS WAS REPLACED AND THE RAILCAR PRESSURE TESTED PRIOR TO ANY FURTHER LOADING.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, KCI HAS ADDED A PRESSURE TEST PROCEDURE TO ITS PRODUCT BENZENE, PHENOL, AND PLASTICIZER RAILCAR LOADING PROCEDURES.  THIS TEST PORCEDURE WILL BE PERFORMED BY NITROGEN PRESSURIZING EACH TANK CAR TO 10 PSI PRESSURE TESTING FOR 30 MIN.
THE FAILURE WAS CAUSED BY AN OPEN CLOSURE VALVE IN OUR UNLOADING SYSTEM AWAY FROM THE  RAIL CAR.

column168: ON OCT 2 1996 A CUSTOMER OF THIS AREA RETURNED A NURSE TANK THAT HE HAD ROLLED OVER IN THE FIELD.  THE SAFETY EQUIPMENT WHICH WE USED WORKED, PREVENTING ANY SPILL INTO THE AIR.  AFTER THE TANK HAD BEEN RIGHTED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK WAS BASICALLY UNDAMAGED. IN ORDER TO GET THE TANK BACK INTO TOWN FOR FURTHER CHECK UP, WE DECIDED TO GO AHEAD AND HAVE TO PLOW APPLY WHAT WAS LEFT IN THE TANK.  THIS WAS DOME WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENTS.  AFTER CLOSE EXAMINATION I DETERMINED THAT I WOULD REPLACE THE SAFETY POP OFF VALVE AND BOTH FILL VALVES.  THE REASON FOR THIS WAS BECAUSE I DID NOT FEEL COMFORTABLE WITH WHAT THE ROLL BAR LOOKED LIKE.  I DECIDED AT THAT TIME TO REPLACE THOSE ITEMS. NEXT I MOVED THE AD TANK TO THE LOADING AREA AND HOOKED THE AD TANK UP TO THE PUMP AND PUMPED OFF ALL THE REMAINING LIQUID INTO THREE TANKS.  JUST TO MAKE ABSOLUTELY POSITIVE THAT THERE WAS NO LIQUID LEFT IN THE TANK.  UPON COMPLETION OF THIS I CRACKED OPEN THE SMALL BLEEDER VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANK.  I ADJUSTED THIS VALVE TO THE POINT THAT I COULD COMPLETELY WALK AROUND AND WORK ON THE TANK WITHOUT MY NH3 MASK FOR PROTECTION.  EVIDENTLY MY PERSONAL TOLERANCE FOR THE SMELL OF ANHYDROUS IS A LOT GREATER THAT MOST PEOPLE.  I FEEL BADLY FOR WHAT HAS TAKEN PLACE SO FAR, BUT I CANT STRESS ANY MORE STRONGER THAT I BELIEVED WITH ALL MY HEART AND SOUL THAT I DOING EVERYTHING RIGHT.  I JUST PLAIN UNDERESTIMATED OTHER PEOPLES TOLERANCE FOR NH3.  THE ONLY THING BEING RELEASED WAS TANK PRESSURE AND NOTHING BEYOND THAT. I CAN TELL YOU NOW THAT I HAVE ALREADY TAKEN MEASURES IN OUR PROCEDURES TO GUARANTEE THAT THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.  THERE WILL BE ACTIONS AND PROCEDURES DISCUSSED AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING FOR THE MONTH OF OCTOBER.
THE FRA INSPECTORS FOUND THE TANK CAR IN THE YARD WITH A LEAKAGE AT THE MANWAY.  THE SHIPPER CALLED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, LCM TO MAKE REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HRS 10/01/96, EMPLOYEES AT 18TH ST YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS, NOTED PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF TANK CAR RAIX 9054, WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED.  CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION AND/OR REPAIR. CAR WAS INSPECTED BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS K C DECHANT AT 2045 HRS THAT DATE.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WSA VISIBLY DISPLACED AT A POINT OPPOSITE THE HINGE.  THE COVER WAS SO LOOSE THAT THE GASKET COULD BE MANUALLY MOVED INTO AND OUT OF POSITION WITHOUT LOOSENING THE SWING BOLTS SECURING IT.  ALL LEAKAGE APPEARED TO HAVE EMANATED FROM THIS POINT.  DECHANT OPENED THE MANWAY COVER, NOTING THAT THE SWING BOLT DIRECTLY ADJACENT TO THE POINT OF GASKET DISPLACEMENT WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT. OTHER SWING BOLTS WERE NOTED TIGHTENED TO VARYING DEGREES.  THE GASKET APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  IT WAS RE-INSTALLED, THE COVER CLOSED, AND SWING BOLTS TIGHTENED PER TORQUE SEQUENCE DISPLAYED ON THE COVER.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  NO PRODUCT IS KNOWN TO HAVE REACHED THE GROUND.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 2140 HRS. AT TIME OF INITIAL INSPECTION, MANWAY COVER WAS PROTECTED BY SEAL UCC-187363, AND VALVE COVER PROTECTED BY UCC-187359.  THEY WERE REPLACED WITH UPE-277483/84 RESPECTIVELY FOLLOWING INSPECTION AND REPAIR.  CHEMTREC FILE # 48392.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HRS 10/02/96, UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM TANK CAR GATX 46152 IN THE UPRR COUNCIL BLUFFS NORTH YARD. CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY INSPECTED BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS K.C. DECHANT AT 1840 HRS THAT DATE.  DECHANT NOTED THAT ALL LEAKAGE WAS FROM AROUND THE THREADS OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE OPEN 1/2 TURN. THE LEAKAGE IMMEDIATELY DIMINISHED UPON CLOSURE OF THE VALVE, AND STOPPED ENTIRELY WITH AN ADDITIONAL 1/2 INCH TURN OF THE OUTLET CAP.  RATE OF LEAKAGE WAS SUCH THAT NO POOLING OR SATURATION OCCURRED, AND ALL LEAKAGE APPEARED TO HAVE EVAPORATED.  INSPECTION DISCLOSED ALL OTHER FITTINGS SECURE, NO EVIDENCE OF ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  CHEMTREC FILE #48391.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN, UT, MGR H W RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR MKT100423 & NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE TOP CONT-ROLLED BOTTOM OUTLET CONTROL ROD WAS LOOSE.  MGR RODABOUGH SECURED THE PACKING GLAND NUT, IN THE PROCESS IT WAS NECESSARY TO REMOVE SEAL AMOCO4423, IT WAS REPLACED WITH UP-X-589584.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED MR TOM FLOREZ FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NMBER 48536.  MR DAVE MORSETTE OF AMOCO OIL ALSO NOTIFIED.

PTLX120151 LD/TANK FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION (CORROSIVE MTL) WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A HOLE ON BR CORNER OF TANK SHELL APP 1/4 OF THE WAY DOWN FROM THE TOP OF TANK, THE HOLE WAS APPROX 1/8" IN DIAMETER ALLOWING A FLOW OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE CREATING A STREAM OF MATL APP 5' LONG.  CHEM-TREK NOTIFIED AT 1404 HRS ON 10/05/96 IL COMMERCE COMMISSION AT 1432 HRS (INCIDENT #961839) AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER NOTIFIED AT 1711 HRS (INCIDENT #363483).  RESPONDERS ON ARRIVAL ATTEMPTED TO PLUG HOLE WITH WOOD DOWEL BUT EVIDENTLY THE CORROSIVE MTL HAD WORKED ITS WAY BETWEEN THE TANK SHELL AND RUBBER LINING AND OVER TIME HAD CORRODED THE METAL ALLOWING THE LEAK TO DEVELOP, THE DEEPER THE PLUG WENT THE LARGER THE HOLE BECAME. SINCE THE FLOW WAS MINIMUM AT THIS TIME IT WAS DECIDED TO TRANSFER THE COMPLETE LOAD INTO TRUCKS AND THIS WAS COMPLETED AT 3:00AM 10/06/96.  APP 60 GALS WAS CONTAINED IN BARRELS AS THE PATCHING PROCESS TOOK PLACE. AREA ON THE GROUND WHERE THE PRODUCT LEAK WAS TREATED WITH CRUSHED LIMESTONE TO NEUTRALIZE THE MATERIAL.  THE CONTAMINATED GROUND SOIL AND CRUSHED LIMESTONE WILL BE CLEANUP FOR DISPOSAL BY OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR.  AT THIS TIME THE CAUSE IS A DEFECTIVE INNER RUBBER LINING. SHIPPER TO PURGE CLEAN THE TANK AT THEIR FACILITY AND TRRA WILL REQUEST HOME SHOP DISPOSITION FROM CAR OWNER FOR MOVEMEMENT HOME FOR REPAIRS.  AT THIS TIME TRRA CONSIDERS THE SHIPPER AS RESPONSIBLE PARTY FOR CLEAN UP.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: DURING AM SORT OPERATION, COURIER IS PULLING SEVEN LARGE BOXES OFF BELT, ALL CONTAINING FIRE EXTINGUISHERS.  THE BOXES ARE MARKED AND LABELED FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, AND DOCUMENTATION IS PRESENT.  ONE OF THE UNITS DISCHARGED AS IT WAS BEING SET ON THE FLOOR WITH THE OTHER BOXES.  A SHORT BLACK HOSE WITH METAL FITTINGS IS PROPELLED FROM THE BOX AND CUTS THE COURIER ON THE HAND.  THE COURIER, JOHN SILVA, WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE 6 STITCHES WERE REQUIRED.  THE COURIER IS THEN RELEASED AND GOES HOME.  LOCAL FEDEX MANAGEMENT IS MONITORING HIS PROGRESS.  DURING THE COURSE OF THESE EVENTS, THE 24-HOUR EMERGENCY NUMBER (CHEMTREC) LISTED ON THE DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION WAS CALLED.  CHEMTREC CONFIRMED SCHUMACHER AS A CLIENT, HOWEVER CHEMTREC HAD NO INFORMATION ON THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER(S).  CHEMTREC DID OFFER TO CONTACT SOMEONE WITH THE PARENT COMPANY (AIR PRODUCTS) AND I RECEIVED A RETURN CALL SHORTLY THEREAFTER. MSDS WAS LATER OBTAINED.  LOCAL FAA/CAFSO WAS NOTIFIED PER 49CFR 171.15 AND .16. FAA AGENT STEVE CRAWFORD INVESTIGATED AND RELEASED ALL THE PACKAGES.  THE CAUSE OF THE DISCHARGE REMAINS UNKNOWN.  RECIPIENT WAS CONTACTED AND PICKED UP ALL PACKAGES FROM THE LOCATION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED INBOUND WHEN THE DAMAGE LEAKAGE OCCURED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ACTUALLY DECLARED AS CONSUMER COMMODITY BUT THE PROBLEM WAS THAT THERE WERE NO OTHER MARKING LABELS NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  A LID ON ONE OF THE INNER CONTAINERS OF CEMENT HAD FAILED AND THIS RESULTED IN THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS MISSORTED TO COLUMBUS, OH, RATHER THAN GOING TO WISCONSIN.  WHEN WE WERE PREPARING TO STAGE IT TO GO OUT WITH THE EVENING OUTBOUND FREIGHT, A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL TWO GLASS "BALL" CANNING JARS.  THESE JARS WERE PLACED INSIDE A PLASTER MOLDED CAST.  THERE WAS NO CUSHIONING NOR ANY ABSORBANT MATERIAL IN THAT BOX.  ONCE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE PACKING INADEQUACIES WITH BOX #1, BOX #2 ON AIRBILL #923-7012-662 WAS OPENED.  IN IT WE FOUND TWO 500 ML METAL CANS WITHOUT POSITIVE CLOSURE, I.E. NO CAN CLIPS OR RING-LOCK. THERE WAS NO PERCEPTIBLE LEAKAGE FROM BOX #2.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE SHIPPER USING THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER AS: 205-854-9296.  THIS NUMBER WAS THE HOME RESIDENCE OF THE SHIPPER, IDENTIFIED AS DONALD KELLY.  I SPOKE TO BOTH MR. KELLY'S DAUGHTER, PAIGE, AS WELL AS HIS WIFE, WHO DID NOT GIVE ME HER NAME.  MRS. KELLY INQUIRED IF THIS WAS THE SAME PKG THAT FEDEX HAD REFUSED?  AS I HAD NO INFO THAT THAT HAD TAKEN PLACE, I ADVISED THAT MY SHIPMENT WAS GOING TO WI.  MRS. KELLY CONFIRMED THAT FEDEX HAD INDEED REFUSED IT IN THE PAST. WHEN I INQUIRED IF EITHER MRS. KELLY OR HER DAUGHTER COULD GIVE ME ANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFO ON CLEANING UP THIS SPILL THEY SAID THAT HER HUSBAND WOULD CALL ME BACK WHEN HE GOT HOME AND THAT HE WOULD BE EXTREMELY UPSET THAT HIS FREIGHT HAD BEEN DAMAGED.  AT THAT POINT I NOTIFIED THE LCK FAA CASFU SPECIAL AGENT SEAN MAHONEY.  THEY SAID THAT HE WOULD CALL ME BACK.  I EXPECT TO TALK WITH HIM ON 10/8/96.  WE WILL HOLD THE FREIGHT FOR AN FAA INSPECTION.

ON 10/16/96 AT 5:30 PM, HARDESTY & SON, INC'S, DRIVER, PAUL VIANNA HAD A SPILL AT ROCHE AUTOMOTIVE, LOCATED AT 12052 MAIN ST., LIBERTYTOWN, MD. APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 5 GALLONS OF LOW SULFUR DIESEL SPILLED ON THE PARKING LOT.  OUR DRIVER WAS IN OUR COMPANY TRUCK.  HE WAS DRIVING A 1987 FORD TRACTOR #43 AND A 1988 FRUEHAUF TRAILER #44.  HE WAS UNLOADING LOW SULFUR DIESEL INTO THE TANK WHEN A FITTING CAME UNSECURED.  HE THEN IMMEDIATELY TURNED EVERYTHING OFF.  JEFF, FROM ROCHE AUTOMOTIVE AND PAUL VIANNA BEGAN TO CLEAN-UP.  A VOLUNTEER FROM FREDERICK CO. FIRE DEPT. WAS ON THE SITE AND HE HELPED TOO.  THE OWNER OF ROCHE AUTOMOTIVE, LARRY HOLTZOPLE WAS CALLED TO THE LOCATION.  A NEIGHBOR, WESLEY M. GLASS WAS ON THE SITE ALSO. THIS SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP. ********** THE DISPATCHER ON DUTY AT HARDESTY & SON WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY.  HE CLAIMS HE COULDN'T GET A HOLD OF TERRY OR NANCY HARDESTY, (WE BOTH WEAR PAGER'S AT ALL TIMES.)  NANCY HARDESTY WAS NOT INFORMED OF THE SPILL UNTIL THURSDAY MORNING AT 11:25 AM.  NANCY CALLED ROCHE AUTOMOTIVE AND SPOKE WITH JEFF WHO RENTS THE STATION.  SHE THEN CALLED THE OWNER, LARRY HOLTZOPLE AND THE NEIGHBOR MR. GLASS.  NANCY INFORMED THEM THAT SHE WAS SENDING OUR SHOP MECHANIC AND OUR SHOP MANAGER TO ACCESS THE SITUATION.  SHE THEN CALLED E.P.A. AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO ART MAY AT 12:00 P.M. ******* AT 1:30 PM THE SHOP MANAGER CALLED TO INFORM US THAT THE SPILL HAD BEEN PROPERLY CLEANED UP, AND THEY WERE LEAVING TO GO TO CLEAN HARBOR TO DISPOSE OF THE WASTE.  PAUL VIANNA IS SCHEDULED TO MEET WITH THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR ON FRIDAY 10/18/96 AT 7:00 AM.  KARL HOOVER WAS INFORMED OF THE IMPORTANCE OF REPORTING ALL SPILLS TO TERRY OR NANCY HARDESTY IMMEDIATELY.  HARDESTY & SON, INC. TAKES HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENTS VERY VERY SERIOUSLY.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: A VEHICLE COLLISION CAUSED OUR TRUCK TO OVERTURN SPILLING THE LOAD OF AGRICULTURAL CHEMICALS. 19 GALLONS OF AGRICULTURAL CHEMICALS WERE SPILLED. 5.5 GALLONS WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. 13.5 GALLONS WERE NON-DOT REGULATED PRODUCTS. LOCAL POLICE, FIRE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE ON SCENE AND MANAGED THE ENTIRE INCIDENT AND CLEAN UP. THE PEOPLE THAT WERE HOSPITALIZED WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED. RESPONSE NUMBER 364088. THE SPILL CLEAN UP (PRODUCTS AND CONTAMINATED SOIL) WAS SEPARATED BY PRODUCT TYPE AND PLACED IN 15 DRUMS. THE DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED TO WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY IN GREAT FALLS, MONTANA. THE PRODUCTS IN EACH DRUM WILL BE EVALUATED AND EITHER USED OR DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. SEE REPORT 96110501A

FLIGHT 330 ARRIVED IN SPOKANE. AFTER PIT OPENED AND PAINT SPRAYER WAS DISCOVERED. THERE WAS A PUDDLE UNDERNEATH THE UNIT (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 QUART). NONE OF THE LIQUID LEAKED INTO ANY SEAMS ON THE AIRCRAFT FLOOR BOARDS. I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AT ABOUT 08:40 AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED ALASKA AIRLINES DISPATCH WHICH THEY IN TURN CONTACTED MAINTENANCE CONTROL. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT TOWELS AND PINK SHOP SOAP. MAINTENANCE CONTROL WAS SATISIFIED WITH THE PROCESS AND RELEASED THE AIRCRAFT. ALSO I NOTIFIED ALASKA AIRLINES ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS AND THE LOCAL FAA OFFICE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DOCKMAN OPENED UP TRAILER AND BEGAN BREAKING IT.  WHEN HE GOT TO THE NOSE HE NOTICED ONE PAIL LEAKING.  HE THEN NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR, AND HE INSTRUCTED HIM TO GET OUT OF THE TRAILER SO HE COULD SEE WHAT THEY WERE DEALING WITH.  THEY THEN PUT DAMAGED MATERIAL IN A POLY LINED SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH FLOOR DRY USED TO CLEAN THE FLOOR.  THEY PUT A COPY OF THE BILL ALONG WITH SHIPPING PAPERS ON THE SALVAGE DRUM AND APPLIED A FLAMMABLE PLACARD TO IT.

column168: MARK CALLANDER DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS UNAWARE THAT THE CUSTOMERS RECEIVING VALVE LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK WAS USED FOR BOTH LOADING AND UNLOADING PURPOSES.  THEREFORE MARK NEVER REALIZED THERE WAS NOT A CHECK VALVE OR (ONE WAY FLOW VALVE) INSTALLED TO PREVENT BACKWARD PRESSURE AND SPILLAGE.

10-9-96:  AT APPROX 1200 WE WERE OUT IN THE WAREHOUSE UNLOADING "C" CONTAINERS.  DAN PULLED A SMALL WET BOX OUT OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS. JUSTINA TOLD HIM TO PUT IT DOWN.  HE PULLED ANOTHER BOX OUT OF THE CONTAINER THAT WAS ALSO WET AND PUT IT DOWN.  JUSTINA AND MYSELF TOLD HIM NOT TO TOUCH THE BOXES AGAIN.  AFTER THE DRIVERS LEFT, JUSTINA AND I PUT RUBBER GLOVES ON AND OPENED THE BOX.  IT WAS FILLED WITH APPROX 100 SM JARS WITH POISON LABELS AND A CAUTION STATEMENT ON EACH JAR INDICATING THE JARS WERE TOXIC.  THEY ALSO HAD A LABEL INDICATING THE HAZ CLASSIFICATION. THE BOX HAD NO OUTSIDE LABELS INDICATING IT WAS HAZARDOUS.  IT HAD NO HAZ PPWK.  WHEN WE WERE OPENING THE BOX, OUR EYES STARTED TO BURN AND SO DID OUR THROATS.  WE OPENED THE WHS DOOR FOR VENTILATION.  WE PUT ALL THE JARS AND THE SOAKING WET BOX IN A COUPLE PLASTIC BAGS.  I SENT A MSG TO OUR HAZ SPECIALIST (JOHN HANDY IN SEA).  HE TOLD ME TO REPORT THE SHIPPER AND GET THE JARS INTO SOMETHING OTHER THAN THE PLASTIC BAG.  I PULLED THE 1996 NORTH AMERICAN EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK AND READ GUIDE #132.  I PUT THE PLASTIC BAG IN A GARBAGE CAN.  I PUT ANOTHER GARBAGE CAN ON TOP SO IT WOULDN'T GET WET.  I CALLED FAA AND SPOKE TO GARY MAJORS WITH THE FAA TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  I ALSO SENT A MESSAGE TO THE ORIGIN STATION FOR A MSDA.  KAYE AUSTIN, DST. MGR.  10-9-96 *********************** 10-9-96  MSG WAS SENT TO OKC REQUESTING CONTACT WITH SHIPPER FOR MSDS. MIKE THOMPSON/AIRBORNE OKC CALLED AND SPOKE TO S. HAYES AT 0915 OKC TIME REQUESTING AN MSDS.  THREE HOURS LATER THE MSDS STILL HAD NOT BEEN RECEIVED.  I CALLED INTERLINK AND SPOKE TO THEIR ANSWERING SERVICE.  I EXPLAINED IT WAS AN EMERGENCY AND STEVE HAYES MUST CONTACT ME IMMEDIATELY AND FAX AN MSDS.  (0930)

column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY, WAS ADVISED THAT CONTAINER MOLU 212549, LOCATED IN THE OLD RAMP INFIELD, SEATTLE, WA WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING. CONTAINER HAD ARRIVED IN THE WELL OF STACK CAR DTTB 73209 LOCATED AS THE FIRST SOUTH CAR IN UPMF RAMP 6.  BOTH WERE ISOLATED AND PROTECTED WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL WARNING TAPE.  THE CONTAINER APPEARED TO BE LEAKING BETWEEN THE NOSE AND LANDING GEAR AREA OF CONTAINER AND CHASSIS. REAR DOORS PROTECTED BY SEAL ROCH, MIDLAND CORP. 17807.  SAHM LIBBY WAS UNABLE TO ENTER THE NOSE OF CONTAINER SINCE IT WAS LOADED WITHIN INCHES OF THE ROOF.  NOTED LIQUID FOAMING ON THE FLOOR IN THE RIGHT REAR CORNER OF THE CONTAINER.  LITMUS STRIP WAS PLACED INTO THE LIQUID RESULTING IN THE STRIP SHOWING THE LIQUID WAS A BASE.  ROCHESTER MIDLAND CORP CONTRACTED FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE, TO CLEAN STACK CAR AND TRANSLOAD CONTAINER INTO A TRAILER.  ***** THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM 2, 275 GALLON TOTES OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION.  BOTH TOTES HAD BEEN LOADED ON WOODEN PALLETS WHICH HAD BEEN CRUSHED.  THE 2" BUNG CLOSURE ON THE TOP OF THE TOTES HAD NOT BEEN SECURED PROPERLY, WHICH CAUSED THE SPILLAGE.  THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER WAS ABSORBED WITH FLOOR DRY IN ORDER TO DRAY THE CONTAINER TO N W ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE, WA FOR CLEANING TO BE COMPLETED.

column168: TANK CAR OBSERVED BY YARD PERSONNEL AT LIVONIA, LA TO BE GIVING OFF A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED AT LIVONIA YARD.  UNION PACIFIC REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T M ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO LIVONIA. ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD SLOSHED FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND WAS SOLIDIFYING ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  ALSO A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR WAS COMING FROM THE SAME AREA. THE SIX BOLTS SECURING THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WERE TIGHT.  ROBINSON CONTACTED MR CORKY HILDEBRAND, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR UNION CARBIDE AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM UNION CARBIDES HELP TEAM.  ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED BY MR JERRY DARRENSBOURG, HELP TEAM LEADER FOR UNION CARBIDE AT TAFT, LA.  DARRENSBOURG ADVISED THAT A HELP TEAM WOULD BE IN ROUTE. DARRENSBOURG AND MR M T FREY OF UNION CARBIDE HELP TEAM RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY INSTALLED.  A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.  AT DARRENSBOURG'S REQUEST, THE CAR WAS REROUTED BACK TO TAFT, LA. DARRENSBOURG RELATED THAT MONDAY MORNING HE WOULD REVIEW THE LOADERS REPORT AND DETERMINE HOW THIS CAR LEFT THE PLANT IN THIS CONDITION. APPROPRIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WILL BE INSTITUTED.

UPRR STO HENRY ALVARADO REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 42451 HAD MOISTURE FROM THE MANWAY AREA DOWN THE SIDE.  THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AT THE TIME. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS COMPRESSED AND ABRADED IN 2 AREAS.  DALE BUNCE OF FMC 913-749-8195, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED.  HE CONFIRMED THAT GORTEX ROPE GASKET WOULD BE APPROPRIATE TO USE WITH THE 80% FOOD GRADE LADING.  THIS WAS APPLIED AND THE CAR RELEASED TO MOVE.  SEALS UPK 831520 AND 831519 WERE REMOVED TO AFFECT REPAIRS.  SEALS UPB 203077 AND 203041 WERE APPLIED TO SECURE THE CAR.  TOM FLORES, CHEMTREC, WAS CALLED.  REPORT #48667.

02:27 - 10/18/96 HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS DIANE FIGUEROA AND ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED TO A SPILL LOCATED INSIDE DOOR K-21 OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS DUE TO THE ODOR PRESENT.  THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH NO OUTER PACKAGE MARKINGS, LABELS OR OTHER ATTACHMENTS TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE REGULATED MATERIALS.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ELECTRONIC EQUIPMENT AND 2 AEROSOL CANS OF "TECH SPRAY DUSTING GAS."  THE CONTENTS OF THESE 2 CANS ARE UNDER PRESSURE WITH HAZARD RATINGS OF HEALTH 1, FIRE 4, REACTIVITY 1. ONE OF THE INNER CANS CLOSURE HAD BECOME DISLODGED DURING TRANSPORT CAUSING APPROX LESS THAN ONE OUNCE OF THE DUSTING GAS TO LEAK.  THE BOX WAS RESEALED, BAGGED AND TAGGED TO BE HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET HAS BEEN REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER AND WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT WHEN OBTAINED.

column168: ON 10/17/96 AT 02:11, HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS DIANE FIGUEROA AND MARTIN CLINE RESPONDED TO A LEAKING SHPT INSIDE DOOR C 20 OF OUR SORT FACILITY. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID WITH THE ODOR OF PAINT.  THEY DONNED PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND OPENED THE BOX. INSIDE THE BOX THEY FOUND 2 METAL QUART CANS FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES. ONE OF THE QUART CANS HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES.  CONTENTS OF THE CANS ARE: "NAPA AUTOMOTIVE FINISHES" WARNING LABEL ON EACH CAN INDICATES THIS IS A FLAMMABLE MATERIAL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RELEASED, BAGGED AND TAGGED TO BE HELD FOR A  MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SORT SECURITY UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER. THE MSDS INDICATES THIS IS A REGULATED MATERIAL, PROPER SHIPPING NAME RESIN SOLUTION, 3 UN 1866, III. THIS SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN ON HOLD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE ARE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET AND SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.

column168: ON 10/10/96 A SPILL WAS REPORTED BY SORT LEAD, VANESSA POLLY.  THE LOCATION IS ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177 IN ONE OF OUR SORT FACILITY BUILDINGS.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TECHNICIANS, CAROLYN CORDREY AND DONNA RESOR RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX.  UPON OPENING THE BOX THEY FOUND A CONDENSATION NUCLEUS COUNTER LEAKING AN ALCOHOL PRODUCT.  CAROLYN EXPLAINED THAT THEY DID NOT KNOW THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THE COUNTER HAD ORIGINALLY CONTAINED.  HOWEVER IT WAS BELIEVED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3 OUNCES OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS FAULTY VALVES AND CLOSURES. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL AND THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

ON 101796 AT ABOUT 6 PM MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM LEE THOMPSON OF CODE 3 ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE. CODE 3 HAD RESPONDED TO TWO LEAKING TRAILERS AT PORT LAREDO.  THE TRAILERS WERE LOADED WITH TOTE BINS OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND SOLIDIFIED.  CODE 3 PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER AND FOUND THE VALVES AT THE BOTTOM OF TWO BINS WERE OPEN.  APPARENTLY THE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED, THEN CRYSTALLIZED OR SOLIDIFIED AROUND THE VALVE.  THEY WERE ABLE TO REACH THE VALVE HANDLES WITH A ROPE AND PULL THEM CLOSED.  SUNAC LISTED CHEMTREC'S TELEPHONE NUMBER FOR EMERGENCIES.  CHEMTREC DID NOT HAVE SUNAC LISTED.  THEY ALSO DID NOT HAVE A LISTING FOR THE MANUFACTURER OF THE MATERIAL, DIACHEN IN VANCOUVER, BC.  CANUTEC WAS EVENTUALLY ABLE TO LOCATE A NUMBER FOR DIACHEN, HOWEVER, AN ANSWERING MACHINE TOOK THE CALL.  A MESSAGE WAS LEFT AND CARL MARKERTH RETURNED THE CALL AT ABOUT 8 PM.  REEDER TOLD MARKERTH THE TRAILER WOULD HAVE TO BE CLEANED AND SECURED BEFORE THEY WOULD BE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: OUR DRIVER PICKED UP TRAILER 104 (EMPTY) AT OUR TERMINAL IN KEARNY, NJ. HE TRAVELED 98 MILES TO LAROCHE INDUSTRIES IN PALMERTON, PA WHERE HE LOADED 6,000 GALLONS OF AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE. AFTER DEPARTING THE PLANT, HE TRAVELED APPROX. 3 MILES. HE CAME TO A STOPPED AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT AND WHEN THE LIGHT TURNED GREEN HE STARTED TO PROCEED UP A HILL ON RTE. 248. HE HEARD A LOUD NOISE, LOOKED IN HIS SIDE-VIEW MIRROR AND SAW THAT THE TRAILER HAD DISCONNECTED. ** THE TRAILER TRAVELED FORWARD APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET AND CAME TO REST WITH THE FRONT END OF THE TRAILER ON THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY AND THE REAR OF THE TRAILER REMAINING IN THE RIGHT LANE OF THE ROADWAY.  **  THERE WAS NO CARGO TANK "FAILURE" AND, TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE, NONE OF THE AMMONIA HYDROXIDE WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND. SOME FUGITIVE VAPORS WERE EMITTED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE FROM THE WASH-OUT CAPS WHICH APPARENTLY LOOSENED WHEN THE TRAILER HIT THE PAVEMENT. THE WASH-OUT CAPS WERE TIGHTENED SHORTLY AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. ** THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED AND SOME OF THE RESIDENTS IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA WERE EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. ** WE SENT IN H.M.H.T.T.C. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO HANDLE THE TRANSFER OF MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER TANK TRAILER. MR. TURNER, WITH H.M.H.T.T.C. INFORMED US THAT NO DECONTAMINATION WAS REQUIRED. THE TRANSFER PRODUCED ONE (1) DRUM OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WHICH INCLUDED DISPOSAL MATERIALS AND RESIDUE RINSED FROM THE TRANSFER HOSES. ** NOTED: WE ARE CERTAIN IF THE EVENTS OF THIS INCIDENT MEET THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE REGULATIONS CONCERNING DOT F 5800. IT IS OUR INTENT TO COMPLY WITH THE BROADEST INTERPRETATION OF SECTION 177.15. ** WE ARE CURRENTLY INVESTIGATING THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT. THE TRACTOR INVOLVED IS A 1996 FREIGHTLINER. THE HOLLAND FIFTH WHEEL WAS REPLACED BY FREIGHTLINER IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ACCIDENT. WE REQUESTED A FORMAL REPORT FROM FREIGHTLINER/HOLLAND AS TO THE REASON FOR THE UNCOUPLING. THIS REPORT IS STILL PENDING.

AT THE END OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE FOREMAN, MR RON ALLEN WENT TO DISCONNECT THE TRANSFER HOSE (AT THE COUPLER) AT THE TRAILER BEING SPLASHED ON HIS CHEST WITH PRODUCT. FOR FOLLOW-UP MR. DANNY MCCREARY (TERMINAL MGR.) AT EVANSVILLE 812-425-9874 IT WAS SUGGESTED THAT STATE NOTIFICATION BE MADE AT TIME THIS REPORT WAS TAKEN. NONE WAS MADE TO BIDS.
