KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN SWITCH CREW REPORTED FINDING A TANK CAR. UCLX 30008, CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SOLUTION, VENTING VAPOR ON TRACK 5, IN KNOCHE. THE SWITCH CREW ISOLATED THE AREA, AND NOTIFIED THE YARDMASTER, THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED, AS WELL AS AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE WHEN THEY ARRIVED, AND FOUND THE TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE FILL HOLE COVER AS RESULT OF AN IMPROPERLY APPLIED GASKET WHICH HAD SLIPPED OUT OF POSITION UNDER THE FILL HOLE COVER. THE LEAK WAS SECURED BY REPOSITIONING THE GASKET AND TIGHTENING THE NUTS AROUND THE FILL HOLE COVER. ONE OF THE SWITCH CREW MEMBERS, MR. VARGIL BRADSHAW, COMPLAINED OF A BURING IN HIS EARS, A TINGLING SENSATION ON HIS FOREHEAD, AND A BAD TASTE IN HIS MOUTH. HE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. ONCE REPAIRS WERE MADE THE CAR, THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO BILLED DESTINATION. NO ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

ECEIVED A CALL TO RESPOND TO A LEAKING PACKAGE ON A UPS PACKAGE CAR ON ESSINGTON AVE.  UPON ARRIVING UPON THE SCENE, I LOOKED AT THE PACKAGE TO IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS, AND OBSERVED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING.  I THEN PUT PPE ON (APRON, GOGGLES, BOOTS, AND GLOVES), AND FOLLOWED DECISION AND RESPONSE TREE.  I THEN WENT TO THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNMARKED PACKAGES. DID STRIP TEST AND GOT A READING OF (5).  I THEN USED THE CORROSIVE SHEET, FOLLOWED INSTRUCTIONS, AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL FOLLOWING ALL DMP PROCEDURES

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY DENNY YARD, OPERATIONS MANAGER, TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO ADVISED AN OUTSIDE DRIVER REPORTED A CONTAINER LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE REAR DOORS. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, IT WAS MOVED TO A TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. AS MANAGER COOPER WAS IN LAS VEGAS AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH ENVIRONMENTAL TRANLOADING SERVICES (ETSI), THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, TO INSPECT THE CONTAINER. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LEAKING COMMODITY TO BE THE LISTED PETROLEUM DISTILLATE. AFTER OBTAINING A MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER, MONSANTO, THE REAR DOOR SEAL, MONSANTO 77952, WAS REMOVED TO INSPECT THE INTERIOR LADING . UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, OBSERVED 3 EACH 2X6 HORIZONTAL BULL BOARDS ACROSS THE BACK OF THE LADING, POSITIONED IN THE SIDEWALL SLOTTED DOOR POST. THESE WERE EVENLY SPACED WITH THE UTILIZATION OF SEVERAL 3 FOOT VERTICAL PIECES NAILED TO EACH CROSS MEMBER. DIRECTLY BEHIND THE LUMBER WAS A SINGLE PIECE OF 4X8 FOOT PLYWOOD, PLACED ON END, AND ONLY PROTECTING THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE LADING. THERE WERE 2 EACH LARGE D.I.D. INFLATABLE BAGS ON END BETWEEN THE LUMBER/PLYWOOD AND SEVERAL LARGE SECTIONS OF 6 INCH CORRUGATED HONEYCOMB FILLER MATERIAL, WHICH SEPARATED THE LADING OF DRUMS. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTIVE FOR DOUBLE STACKED LADING OF DRUMS, AND IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR TRANSPORTATION. ** DUE TO THE CONFIGURATION OF THE DOUBLE STACKED DRUMS, IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WITHOUT OFF LOADING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH APL, THE RAILROADS SHIPPER OF RECORD, TO AUTHORIZE THE TRANSLOAD OPERATION AND PROVIDE A BACK UP CONTAINER. DUE TO THE BASE CONSTITUENT OF THE PRODUCT BEING XYLENE, IT WAS DECIDED TO PLACED THE LADING INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE, AND THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WOULD FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE, AND THE ORGINAL CONTAINER WOULD BE MOVED TO APL'S M&R GROUP FOR INSPECTION AND DETERMINATION AS TO WHETHER THE FLOOR WOULD REQUIRE REMOVAL OR JUST CLEANING OF THE RESIDUE IMBEDDED IN THE WOOD FLOORING. ** APL PROVIDED EMPTY CONTAINER APLS 286343, WHICH WAS GROUNDED ADJACENT TO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, AS THERE IS NO LOADING DOCK TO WORK FROM WITHIN THE INTERMODAL FACILITY. ** THE OPERATION REMOVED THE DRUMS, WHICH WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINER. NEAR THE NOSE OF THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, LOCATED 4 DRUMS THAT WERE LEAKING. THE DRUMS WERE ALL FROM THE FIRST 2 ROWS NEAR THE NOSE, AND ALL FROM THE FLOOR LEVEL. DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING OF THE DRUMS IN A OFF SET PATTERN EVERY OTHER DRUM, RATHER THAN A STRAIGHT LINE OF 3, THEN OFF SETTING THE 4TH DRUM, THE ENTIRE LOAD HAD SHIFTED TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER, ALLOWING A 5 INCH GAP DOWN THE ENTIRE SIDE. THIS VOID ALLOWED

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: ON 10/29/96 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, SPILL TECHNICIAN, SUE HICKEY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL SHE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS SHE FOUND AN ANIMAL, TISSUE SAMPLE, IN A CLEAR FLUID.  IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THE FLUID WAS ETHANOL SOLUTION.  THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 OUNCES OF FLUID.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  TO INCIDATE THIS TO BE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTGATION.

TRAILER ARRIVED IN CHARESTON, 26-3490, ON MORNING OF 10/16/96.  AFTER REMOVING A PORTION OF FREIGHT DISCOVERED SHIPMENT PRO 756840431.  1 DRUMS WAS LEAKING WHERE IT WAS HIT AND RUPTURED.  CARDBOARD WAS UNDER ALL (6) DRUMS.  APPROXIMATELY A QUART HAD SPILLED. JOE FRITH OF OVERNITE ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES WAS CONTACTED, AND ADVISED TO CALL CLEAN UP AT FENN-CAC. LEAKING DRUM WAS REPACKED BY DENN VAC AND CLEAN UP COMPLETED. THE PRODUCT WAS HIGHLY CORROSIVE.  THE GAFFNEY TERMINAL SHOULD MONITOR FREIGHT TO AVOID FORWARDING LEAKING FREIGHT.
DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE, AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DMP PROGRAM. PLACED WASTE IN PLASTIC BAG AND ALSO PROCESSED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 19-4191, B PRESSLEY, FOUND A CTN WET AND LEAKING WITHIN.  CTN WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE CAUSING IT TO LEAK AT THE CAP. RECOUPED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND HOLDING IN OS&D.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 102296 AT APPROXIMATLEY 2230 HRS SPECIAL AGENT J. WALTHAL NOTIFIED CTS MGR. M. KELLY THAT THE ABOVE CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED TO HIM AS LEAKING BY A CARMAN IN THE YARD.  UPON HIS ARRIVAL KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS CRACKED.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION.

THE RESPONDER USED PROPER PPE.  UPS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BOOK WAS USED TO VERIFY UN NUMBER.  THE DECISION TREE WAS USED FOR CORROSIVE.  I USED CLAY ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY BAGGED AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT PACKED IN A DOT REGULATED BOX, NO TOP OR BOTTOM PADDING, CARDBOARD DIVIDER, NO DIAMOND LABELS, OR CAUTIONARY MARKINGS, DIDN'T HAVE ENOUGH CUSHIONING, OR REINFORCED KRAFT TAPE. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DURING A ROUTINE DELIVERY OF VAPAM IN THE VICINITY OF ROAD 7 NW AND ROAD H, A TRUCK DRIVEN BY NEXUS AG CHEMICALS OVERTURNED AND SPILLED A LARGE PORTION OF ITS LOAD.  THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ON THE PROPERTY OF HAROLD LEWIS AND ACCUMULATED IN A DITCHED SECTION BETWEEN ROAD 7 NW AND AN IRRIGATION CHANNEL (SEE ILLUSTRATION "A").  OF THE 27,6000 LBS OF VAPAM LIQUID THAT WAS INSIDE THE TANK ALL BUT 6,320 LBS WAS LOST INTO THE SOIL.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS ABLE TO MAKE HIS WAY OVER TO THE RESIDENCE OF HAROLD LEWIS AND CALL BACK TO NEXUS.  THIS CALL WAS RECEIVED ABOUT 7:05 AM ON THE MORNING OF OCTOBER 17, 1996.  A TOTAL OF 21,280 LBS OF LIQUID WAS LOST FROM THE VEHICLES STORAGE TANK, WHICH 42% CONSISTED OF THE ACTIVE INGREDIENT SODIUM METHYLDITHICARBOMATE THAT MAKES UP VAPAM.

ON OCTOBER 12,1996, A RELEASE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO THE ATMOSPHERE CAUSED BY A STRUCTURE CRACK IN A UNLOADING VALVE UNDER THE DOME OF A RAILCAR.  THE RAILCAR WAS A DUPONT CAR, NUMBER 26710, RECEIVED AT OUR FACILITY AROUND  2:00 PM OCTOBER 12, 1996.  THE LEAK WAS IDENTIFIED AT 7:50 PM BY FOLLOWING A ODOR OF AMMONIA.  DEGUSSA PERSONNEL RESPONDED, BUT ATTEMPTS WITH ON SCENCE REPAIR WERE UNSUCCESSFUL, THEREFORE THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE UNIT FOR OFFLOADING.  EMISSIONS WERE CONTROLLED DURING OFFLOADING BY VENTING TO A FLARE.  WE ESTIMATE APPROXIMATELY 500 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE DURING THE EVENT.  ON OCTOBER 12, 1996 TELEPHONE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO BOTH LEPC, NRC AND SERC.  THE NRC REPORT NUMBER IS 364215. THERE WERE NO REPORTED MEDICAL INSTANCES NOR ANY ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ON THE SURROUNDING COMMUNITY.
